Lessons that can still be learned from the Cuban Missile Crisis
"Thirteen Days" („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, is set to open in cinemas in numerous countries soon.
Everyone should watch this film, not only because it deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events—particularly regarding the controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system, as well as the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called together his closest advisors at the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a station for nuclear weapons on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be reached, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened during these days in the White House.
Tape recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the premiere of the film in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard initiated a discussion session intended to examine the film and the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this round included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a Harvard history professor who wrote a book on the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a Harvard political science professor who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
In addition, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was present.
Although the cinematic treatment of the subject was criticized in various respects, the discussion participants agreed that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures President Kennedy faced, as they actually were.
What conclusions can we draw today from the Cuban Missile Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be revealed that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how the opponent thinks; in addition, the communication lines must remain open.
To corner an opponent without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow for an understanding of the opponent's situation could turn out to be disastrous.
· The United States depends on allies.
Kennedy therefore acted in this way because the NATO, other allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
A certain amount of time is needed to make good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into taking action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were examined and weighed with the utmost precision was crucial to the outcome.
But would such a temporal margin for weighing considerations still exist today in light of the currently existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy had imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intentions, and not as a means to stop specific Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the USA had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed concern regarding the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had with respect to Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved through the outcomes of the Cuban Missile Crisis," as claimed by the historian Ernest May.
"Too late will be soon," was a widely held argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba, even while the missiles—assuming they were on their way to Cuba by sea—were en route.
A U.S. force of approximately 180,000 troops was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a lightning bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there had already been nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, of which 90 were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew."
And I have explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the eradication of Cuba.
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba burn to ashes so that their nation would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion, therefore, could have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion would "certainly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the United States.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: planes of the U-2 type, flying through Cuban airspace, were shot down despite the chairman's explicit instructions to the contrary.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who during the crisis was distinguished by a more rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
In light of the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
The current discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat posed by nuclear blackmail by rogue states should take place in light of this terrible, yet entirely realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the Internet where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
